<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">GE Profile is GE's smart-appliance tier — TwinChill evaporators, Turbo Cool, built-in WiFi — and the refrigerator is what we repair most, especially the French door models in Glendale, Burbank, and Pasadena where Profile is the go-to mid-luxury choice.</h2>

    <p>Profile sits at the entry-premium tier in GE Appliances' US lineup — above the standard GE line, below GE Café (the design-forward mid-luxury tier), well below GE Monogram (the full-luxury built-in tier). The positioning lands consistently in our service area: Profile shows up in the $40K-$70K kitchen renovation, in the mid-luxury condominium build, in the new construction where the developer specified "smart features" as a selling point. Glendale (Adams Hill, Verdugo Woodlands, La Crescenta), Burbank (Magnolia Park, Toluca Lake, downtown condos), Pasadena (the 2000s-onward townhouse and condo developments), and Alhambra (San Gabriel Valley renovation kitchens) anchor the bulk of our Profile service volume. Westside neighborhoods carry Profile installations too, but the Westside skews higher into Café and Monogram; in the Valley and the foothills, Profile is the default mid-luxury choice. Refrigerator service runs roughly 60% of our Profile call volume — driven heavily by the PFE28 French door TwinChill pattern that's now well into its in-service failure window.</p>

    <p>Three Profile-specific realities shape every service call we run. First, <strong>Profile's TwinChill dual-evaporator architecture is the centerpiece feature on the PFE-series French door fridges and it drives a distinctive failure pattern</strong>. TwinChill runs two separate evaporators with two separate circulation fans — one for the freezer compartment, one for the fresh-food side. The advantage is independent temperature control and reduced cross-compartment humidity. The service implication is that a fan failure on one side produces the signature "freezer fine, fridge warm" symptom that's almost diagnostic on its own. The 2017-2022 PFE28 production cohort is now in the year 4-5 service window where that fresh-food evap fan motor wears out. Second, <strong>Profile is distinct from Café and Monogram even though all three are GE Appliances brands</strong> — different chassis platforms, different control boards, different parts numbering. Profile model numbers start with P (PFE, PSB, PDT, PGB), Café with C, Monogram with Z, and we identify the tier from the inside-door tag before any parts get ordered. Third, <strong>Haier ownership doesn't affect Profile parts availability</strong> — Haier acquired GE Appliances in 2016, but Louisville KY remains the engineering and distribution headquarters, the US parts network is intact, and 2-5 day lead times are standard six-plus years post-acquisition.</p>

    <p>This page covers Profile repair across the full US lineup — refrigerators (the bulk of the work), ranges, wall ovens, dishwashers, washers and dryers, microwaves, cooktops. Every Profile service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM Profile parts via GE Appliances' US distribution, and an honest written quote with parts lead-time disclosed before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 REFRIGERATORS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Profile refrigerator repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">PFE28 French door TwinChill, PSB built-in side-by-side, bottom-freezer.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Refrigerator service dominates our Profile service mix — around 60% of every Profile call. The lineup splits across three install patterns: PFE-series French door (counter-depth and standard-depth, all with TwinChill dual-evaporator architecture and most with built-in WiFi), PSB-series built-in side-by-side (42-inch and 48-inch widths for kitchens that specified built-in dimensions without going up to Monogram tier), and bottom-freezer variants.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>2017-2022 PFE28 TwinChill evaporator fan pattern (most common Profile service call in LA)</h3>
      <p>The PFE28KYNFS and surrounding PFE28 production years between roughly 2017 and 2022 develop a consistent TwinChill fresh-food evaporator fan motor failure around year 4 to 5. The signature symptom is almost diagnostic on its own: <strong>fridge compartment running warm (45-55°F) while the freezer holds setpoint normally (around 0°F).</strong> Cause: the TwinChill system runs separate evaporators with separate fans for fresh-food and freezer; the fresh-food fan motor bearings wear, the fan runs at reduced RPM, eventually stops entirely, and cold air stops circulating to the refrigerator side even though the freezer side keeps working perfectly. Sometimes the symptom develops gradually (fridge running 42°F → 46°F → 50°F over a week), sometimes it presents overnight. Replacement runs $245-$385 and is typically same-day when we stock the PFE28 evap fan motors on the truck. Worth pairing with a defrost system check at the same visit — if the fresh-food evap had been running under stress, frost buildup may have accumulated and a paired heater/thermostat check confirms the system is healthy after the fan replacement.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the TwinChill pattern, Profile refrigerator service tree covers a predictable set of items by year-window:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 2-4:</strong> Ice maker fill valve ($185-$285) in hard-water LA addresses (San Gabriel Valley, Valley side of the hills — most of our Profile service territory runs hard water), water inlet valve ($185-$285), door gasket replacement on heavily-used French door units.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 4-5:</strong> TwinChill fresh-food evap fan motor (above) — the dominant PFE28 service item.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-7:</strong> Ice maker assembly ($345-$525), defrost system (heater + thermostat + bimetal, $245-$385), Turbo Cool fan motor on variants that have it ($245-$385).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-10:</strong> Condenser fan motor ($285-$425), main control board ($345-$525), damper control assembly ($185-$345 — splits cold air between fresh-food and freezer on integrated airflow variants), LED light panel ($185-$285).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10+:</strong> Compressor or sealed-system work ($580-$880). Repair-vs-replace math runs case-by-case at this point — Profile French door replacement is $1,800-$3,500, so a compressor swap at $700 is reasonable through year 12 but starts to get closer to replacement-cost on entry-tier PFE variants.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>WiFi Connect / SmartHQ integration on Profile French door units is cosmetic-not-functional for the refrigerator itself — the fridge cools whether or not the app is connected. WiFi-side failures (app shows offline, remote temperature setting not responding, firmware update stuck) split into software issues that resolve with credential reset or app reauthentication, and hardware issues where the WiFi communication board itself has failed ($185-$345 replacement). Diagnostic separates which on-site. PSB-series built-in side-by-side units (42-inch and 48-inch widths) and bottom-freezer variants share most of the Profile refrigerator parts catalog but install differently — built-in installs require cabinetry-flush preservation during pull-work, similar discipline to Monogram column work though less demanding.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 RANGES, OVENS, COOKTOPS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Ranges, wall ovens, cooktops</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">PGB gas ranges, PTS smart wall ovens, the Profile cooking surface lineup.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Outside refrigeration, Profile's cooking lineup covers freestanding and slide-in gas ranges (PGB-series dominant), induction ranges (PHS), electric ranges (PB), single and double wall ovens (PTS smart wall ovens with WiFi, PT standard configurations), and 30-inch and 36-inch gas / induction / electric cooktops.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Ranges (PGB gas, PHS induction)</h3>
        <p>PGB911SEJSS and family of slide-in gas ranges dominate the LA Profile cooking mix. Service: oven igniter ($185-$285) year 3-5 typical, surface burner igniter ($145-$245), oven thermostat ($245-$385), convection fan motor ($285-$425), oven door hinge ($185-$285), gas valve assembly ($345-$525). PHS induction ranges add induction-module service ($385-$580 per zone) to the standard cooking-side service tree.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Wall Ovens (PTS, PT series)</h3>
        <p>PTS9200SNSS WiFi-enabled smart wall ovens and PT standard configurations, single and double, 27-inch and 30-inch widths. Service: bake / broil element ($245-$385), oven temperature sensor ($185-$285), control board ($345-$525), convection fan motor ($285-$425), door hinge alignment ($185-$285). Smart-feature side splits into software-vs-hardware diagnostic (same as Profile refrigerators).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Cooktops (gas, induction, electric)</h3>
        <p>30-inch and 36-inch Profile cooktops across gas (PGP), induction (PHP), and electric (PP) configurations. Gas service: igniter ($185-$285), spark module ($245-$385), burner valve. Induction service: surface element / induction module ($385-$580), control board ($345-$525), pan-detection sensor. Electric: radiant element ($245-$385).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Microwaves (PVM, PEM)</h3>
        <p>PVM over-the-range microwaves and PEM countertop units. Service: magnetron tube ($385-$580), waveguide cover, door switch ($185-$285), turntable motor ($185-$285), control panel ($345-$525). Some PVM variants include sensor-cooking with humidity sensing on the high tier.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Shared parts with Café (entry-premium)</h3>
        <p>Many Profile cooking components are shared with GE Café at the entry-premium level (igniters, surface elements, certain control boards, water valves). Practical effect: better parts availability than tier-specific luxury brands, often same-day or next-day on common service items via GE Appliances' US network.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Smart-feature diagnostic discipline</h3>
        <p>WiFi-enabled Profile cooking units (PTS wall ovens, smart ranges) require the software-vs-hardware diagnostic split. Connectivity failures often resolve without parts. Core appliance functions (heat, bake, broil) work regardless of WiFi status — smart features are cosmetic-not-functional layer.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 DISHWASHERS, LAUNDRY -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Dishwashers, washers, dryers</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">PDT smart dishwashers, PFW870 SmartDispense front-load laundry, PTD top-load.</h2>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Dishwashers (PDT series)</h3>
        <p>PDT845SYVFS and PDT715SYNFS smart dishwashers with third rack and stainless tubs. Service: drain pump ($245-$385) year 4-6 typical, circulation pump ($385-$580), water inlet valve ($185-$285), heating element ($245-$385), control board ($345-$525), door latch ($185-$285), door seal ($185-$285). Third-rack alignment service ($145-$245 labor-only) when the upper-rack mechanism gets out of true.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Front-Load Washers (PFW870 SmartDispense)</h3>
        <p>PFW870 SmartDispense front-load washers — automated detergent / softener dosing system that holds bulk supply and meters per-cycle. Service: SmartDispense pump ($245-$385 — dedicated metering pumps, distinct from main drain pump), drain pump ($245-$385), door boot seal ($185-$345), shock absorbers ($285-$425), control board ($345-$525). SmartDispense pump failures present as detergent not dispensing or over-dispensing — software / hardware split applies here too.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Dryers (PFD870, PTD60)</h3>
        <p>PFD870 front-load gas/electric dryers and PTD60 top-load. Service: heating element on electric ($185-$285), gas valve / igniter on gas dryers ($185-$345), thermistor ($185-$285), drum belt ($185-$285), drum roller bearings ($245-$385), control board ($345-$525), door switch.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Top-Load Washers (PTW60)</h3>
        <p>PTW60 high-efficiency top-load washers. Service: agitator coupler ($145-$285), drain pump ($245-$385), lid lock / lid switch ($185-$285), control board ($345-$525), water inlet valve, drive motor on direct-drive variants ($385-$580).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>SmartDispense software vs hardware</h3>
        <p>SmartDispense failures split into software (app misconfiguration, dispense schedule wrong, supply-level sensor reading bad) vs hardware (metering pump failed, supply tank seal leaking, line clogged). Diagnostic separates which — software resolves without parts, hardware is a $245-$385 pump replacement plus possible $185-$285 line service.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Honest repair-vs-replace math</h3>
        <p>Profile units run $1,500-$4,000 each — fridge $1,800-$3,500, range $1,500-$3,000, dishwasher $1,200-$2,000, front-load washer $1,400-$2,400, dryer $1,200-$2,200. Against typical service costs of $200-$580 per repair, repair wins comfortably through year 8-10 across all categories. We tell you when math gets close at year 12+.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 MODELS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Models we service most often</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Profile model families in heavy SoCal service rotation.</h2>

    <p class="lead">A representative sample of Profile model families our techs service routinely. Not exhaustive — the full Profile catalog covers more variants — but covers the units that show up most often on our route.</p>

    <div class="model-grid">
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>French Door Refrigerators (PFE series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">PFE28KYNFS · PFE28KSKSS · PFE28PYNFS · PFE29PSDSS</p>
        <p>Counter-depth and standard-depth French door with TwinChill dual-evaporator architecture. The 2017-2022 PFE28 cohort carries the fresh-food evap fan failure pattern.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Built-In Side-by-Side (PSB series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">PSB48YSKSS · PSB42YSKSS · PSB48YPKFS · PSB42YPKFS</p>
        <p>42-inch and 48-inch built-in side-by-side — entry-built-in tier below Monogram ZISS, fits the same cabinet openings at a lower price point.</p>
